# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cvss-scoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The **Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures** (**CVE**) system, originally **Common Vulnerability Enumeration**, provides a reference method for publicly known information-security vulnerabilities and exposures.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The United States' Homeland Security Systems Engineering and Development Institute FFRDC, operated by The MITRE Corporation, maintains the system, with funding from the US National Cyber Security Division of the US Department of Homeland Security.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The system was officially launched for the public in September 1999.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The Security Content Automation Protocol uses CVE, and CVE IDs are listed on MITRE's system as well as the basis for the US National Vulnerability Database.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] MITRE Corporation's documentation defines CVE Identifiers (also called "CVE names", "CVE numbers", "CVE-IDs", and "CVEs") as unique, common identifiers for publicly known information-security vulnerabilities in publicly released software packages.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Historically, CVE identifiers originally had a status of "candidate" ("CAN-") and could then be promoted to entries ("CVE-"), but this practice was ended in 2005 and all identifiers are now assigned as CVEs.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The assignment of a CVE number is not a guarantee that it will become an official CVE entry (e.g., a CVE may be improperly assigned to an issue which is not a security vulnerability, or which duplicates an existing entry).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] If found not to meet criteria, MITRE or a CVE Numbering Authority (CNA) can summarily place the entry into REJECTED status.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVEs are assigned by a CVE Numbering Authority (CNA).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] While some vendors acted as a CNA before, the name and designation was not created until 1 February 2005.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Researchers, in one case, have been granted the CNA role.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] When investigating a vulnerability or potential vulnerability it helps to acquire a CVE number early on.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The benefit of early CVE candidacy is that all future correspondence and coordination can refer to the CVE number to ensure all parties are referring to the same vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Information on getting CVE identifiers for issues with open source projects is available from Red Hat and GitHub.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVEs are for software that has been publicly released; this can include betas and other pre-release versions if they are widely used.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Commercial software is included in the "publicly released" category, but custom-built software that is not distributed would historically not be given a CVE.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For the first two decades of the program, services (e.g., a Web-based email provider) are not assigned CVEs for vulnerabilities found in the service (e.g., an XSS vulnerability) unless the issue exists in an underlying software product that is publicly distributed.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Official rules have not been published regarding this change but some CNAs including MITRE have begun assigning CVEs to service-based vulnerabilities as far back as 2000.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This is a standardized text description of the issue(s).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This means that the entry number has been reserved by Mitre for an issue or a CNA has reserved the number.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] So when a CNA requests a block of CVE numbers in advance (e.g., Red Hat currently requests CVEs in blocks of 500), the CVE number will be marked as reserved even though the CVE itself may not be assigned by the CNA for some time.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Until the CVE is assigned, Mitre is made aware of it (i.e., the embargo passes and the issue is made public), and Mitre has researched the issue and written a description of it, entries will show up as "** RESERVED **".
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For CVEs assigned directly by Mitre, this is the date Mitre created the CVE entry.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] For CVEs assigned by CNAs (e.g., Microsoft, Oracle, HP, Red Hat) this is also the date that was created by Mitre, not by the CNA.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] When a CNA requests a block of CVE numbers in advance, the entry date is when the block was assigned to the CNA.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The following fields were previously used in CVE records, but are no longer used.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] In order to support CVE IDs beyond CVE-YEAR-9999 (an issue known as the 'CVE10k problem') a change was made to the CVE syntax in 2014 and took effect on 13 January 2015.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The variable-length arbitrary digits begin at four fixed digits and expand with arbitrary digits only when needed in a calendar year; for example, CVE-YYYY-NNNN and if needed CVE-YYYY-NNNNN, CVE-YYYY-NNNNNN, and so on.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The schema is compatible with previously assigned CVE-IDs, which all include a minimum of four digits.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The Mitre CVE database can be searched at the CVE List Search, and the NVD CVE database can be searched at Search CVE and CCE Vulnerability Database.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Users who have been assigned a CVE identifier for a vulnerability are encouraged to ensure that they place the identifier in any related security reports, web pages, emails, and so on.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Per section 7 of the CNA Rules, a vendor which received a report about a security vulnerability has full discretion in regards to it.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] This can lead to a conflict of interest as a vendor may attempt to leave flaws unpatched by denying a CVE assignment at first place – a decision which Mitre can't reverse.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] The "!CVE" (not CVE) project, announced in 2023, aims to collect vulnerabilities that are denied by vendors, so long as they are considered valid by a panel of experts from the project.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] CVE identifiers have been awarded for bogus issues and issues without security consequences.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] In response, a number of open-source projects have themselves applied to become the CVE Numbering Authority (CNA) of their own project.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] On 15 April 2025, it was reported that the contract between MITRE and the US government, set to expire the day after, would be allowed to expire.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Reports stated that the expiration of the contract would bring an end to the operational arm of the CVE program, including assigning new CVEs, while the database would remain accessible via GitHub.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Just prior to its expiration, the contract was extended for 11 months, averting the shutdown of the program.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Following the risk of funding expiration on March 16, 2026, the acting director of CISA Nick Andersen stated that the program is now being fully funded.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerabilities-and-exposures] Pete Allor, the co-founder of CVE Foundation, reported that the CVE programs funding had been restructured from a discretionary item to being one of the core programs to be funded.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The **Common Vulnerability Scoring System** (**CVSS**) is a framework for rating the severity of computer system vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Scores are calculated from metrics that approximate the ease and impact of exploits.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Scores range from 0 (minor) to 10 (severe).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] While many use only the CVSS Base score for determining severity, temporal and environmental scores also exist, to account for the availability of mitigations and the number of vulnerable systems within an organization, respectively.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The current version of CVSS (CVSSv4.0) was released in November 2023.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] CVSS is not intended as a method for patch prioritization, but is often used as one regardless.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] A more effective approach is to integrate CVSS with predictive models like the Exploit Prediction Scoring System (EPSS), to prioritize remediation based on the likelihood of real-world exploitation.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Research by the National Infrastructure Advisory Council (NIAC) in 2003/2004 led to the launch of CVSS version 1 (CVSSv1) in February 2005, being "designed to provide open and universally standard severity ratings of software vulnerabilities".
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This initial draft was not subject to outside review.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] In April 2005, NIAC selected the Forum of Incident Response and Security Teams to further develop CVSS.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Feedback from vendors using CVSSv1 found "significant issues with the initial draft".
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Work on CVSSv2 began in April 2005 with the final specification being launched in June 2007.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Further feedback lead to work on CVSS version 3 in 2012, with CVSSv3.0 being released in June 2015.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] 3. environmental metrics for vulnerabilities that depend on a particular implementation or environment.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] A score is generated for each group and a vector string represents the values of all the metrics as a block of text.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Complete documentation for CVSSv2 is available from FIRST.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The access vector (AV) shows how a vulnerability may be exploited.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The access complexity (AC) metric describes how easy or difficult it is to exploit the discovered vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The authentication (Au) metric describes the number of times that an attacker must authenticate to a target to exploit it.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] It does not include (for example) authentication to a network in order to gain access.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] For locally exploitable vulnerabilities, this value should only be set to Single or Multiple if further authentication is required after initial access.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The confidentiality (C) metric describes the impact on the confidentiality of data processed by the system.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Integrity (I) metric describes the impact on the integrity of the exploited system.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The availability (A) metric describes the impact on the availability of the target system.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Attacks that consume network bandwidth, processor cycles, memory, or any other resources affect the availability of a system.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] These six metrics are used to calculate the exploitability and impact sub-scores of the vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] These sub-scores are used to calculate the overall base score.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The metrics are concatenated to produce the CVSS Vector for the vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This would give an exploitability score of 10, and an impact score of 8.5, giving a base score of 9.0.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The vector for this example's base score is AV:N/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:P/A:C.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The score and vector are normally presented together to allow recipients to fully understand the vulnerability and to calculate their own score if necessary.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The value of temporal metrics change over the lifetime of the vulnerability, as exploits are developed, disclosed and automated and as mitigations and fixes are made available.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The exploitability (E) metric describes the current state of exploitation techniques or automated exploitation code.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The remediation level (RL) of a vulnerability allows the temporal score of a vulnerability to decrease as mitigations and official fixes are made available.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The report confidence (RC) of a vulnerability measures the level of confidence in the existence of the vulnerability and also the credibility of the technical details of the vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] These three metrics are used in conjunction with the base score that has already been calculated to produce the temporal score for the vulnerability with its associated vector.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This would give a temporal score of 7.3, with a temporal vector of E:P/RL:U/RC:UC (or a full vector of AV:N/AC:L/Au:N/C:P/I:P/A:C/E:P/RL:U/RC:UC).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] A temporary fix from the vendor would reduce the score back to 7.3 (E:P/RL:T/RC:C), while an official fix would reduce it further to 7.0 (E:P/RL:O/RC:C).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] As it is not possible to be confident that every affected system has been fixed or patched, the temporal score cannot reduce below a certain level based on the vendor's actions, and may increase if an automated exploit for the vulnerability is developed.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The environmental metrics use the base and current temporal score to assess the severity of a vulnerability in the context of the way that the vulnerable product or software is deployed.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This measure is calculated subjectively, typically by affected parties.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The collateral damage potential (CDP) metric measures the potential loss or impact on either physical assets such as equipment (and lives), or the financial impact upon the affected organisation if the vulnerability is exploited.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The target distribution (TD) metric measures the proportion of vulnerable systems in the environment.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Three further metrics assess the specific security requirements for confidentiality (CR), integrity (IR) and availability (AR), allowing the environmental score to be fine-tuned according to the users' environment.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The five environmental metrics are used in conjunction with the previously assessed base and temporal metrics to calculate the environmental score and to produce the associated environmental vector.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This would give an environmental score of 8.2, and an environmental vector of CDP:MH/TD:H/CR:H/IR:H/AR:L.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This score is within the range 7.0-10.0, and therefore constitutes a critical vulnerability in the context of the affected bank's business.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Several vendors and organizations expressed dissatisfaction with CVSSv2.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Risk Based Security, which manages the Open Source Vulnerability Database, and the Open Security Foundation jointly published a public letter to FIRST regarding the shortcomings and failures of CVSSv2.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The authors found a lack of granularity in several metrics, which results in CVSS vectors and scores that do not distinguish vulnerabilities of different type and risk profiles.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The CVSS scoring system was also noted as requiring too much knowledge of the exact impact of the vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Oracle introduced the new metric value of "Partial+" for Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability, to fill perceived gaps in the description between Partial and Complete in the official CVSS specifications.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] To address some of these criticisms, development of CVSS version 3 started in 2012.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] CVSSv3.0 was released in June 2015 with a Specification Document, User Guide and Examples document.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Several metrics were changed, added, and removed.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The numerical formulas were updated to incorporate new metrics while retaining the existing scoring range of 0-10.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Textual severity ratings of None (0), Low (0.1-3.9), Medium (4.0-6.9), High (7.0-8.9), and Critical (9.0-10.0) were defined, similar to the categories NVD defined for CVSSv2 that were not part of that standard.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] In the Base vector, the new metrics User Interaction (UI) and Privileges Required (PR) were added to help distinguish vulnerabilities that required user interaction or user or administrator privileges to be exploited.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Previously, these concepts were part of the Access Vector metric of CVSSv2.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] UI can take the values None or Required; attacks that do not require logging in as a user are considered more severe.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] PR can take the values None, Low, or High; similarly, attacks requiring fewer privileges are more severe.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Base vector also saw the introduction of the new Scope (S) metric, which was designed to make clear which vulnerabilities may be exploited and then used to attack other parts of a system or network.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] These new metrics allow the Base vector to more clearly express the type of vulnerability being evaluated.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability (C, I, A) metrics were updated to have scores consisting of None, Low, or High, rather than the None, Partial, and Complete of CVSSv2.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This allows more flexibility in determining the impact of a vulnerability on CIA metrics.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Access Complexity was renamed Attack Complexity (AC) to make clear that access privileges were moved to a separate metric.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] This metric now describes how repeatable exploit of this vulnerability may be; AC is High if the attacker requires perfect timing or other circumstances (other than user interaction, which is also a separate metric) which may not be easily duplicated on future attempts.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Attack Vector (AV) saw the inclusion of a new metric value of Physical (P), to describe vulnerabilities that require physical access to the device or system to perform.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Temporal metrics were essentially unchanged from CVSSv2.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Environmental metrics of CVSSv2 were completely removed and replaced with essentially a second Base score, known as the Modified vector.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The Modified Base is intended to reflect differences within an organization or company compared to the world as a whole.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] New metrics to capture the importance of Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability to a specific environment were added.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] In a blog post in September 2015, the CERT Coordination Center discussed limitations of CVSSv2 and CVSSv3.0 for use in scoring vulnerabilities in emerging technology systems such as the Internet of Things.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] A minor update to CVSS was released on June 17, 2019.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The goal of CVSSv3.1 was to clarify and improve upon the existing CVSSv3.0 standard without introducing new metrics or metric values, allowing for frictionless adoption of the new standard by both scoring providers and scoring consumers alike.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Usability was a prime consideration when making improvements to the CVSS standard.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Several changes being made in CVSSv3.1 are to improve the clarity of concepts introduced in CVSSv3.0, and thereby improve the overall ease of use of the standard.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] FIRST has used input from industry subject-matter experts to continue to enhance and refine CVSS to be more and more applicable to the vulnerabilities, products, and platforms being developed over the past 15 years and beyond.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Updates to the CVSSv3.1 specification include clarification of the definitions and explanation of existing base metrics such as Attack Vector, Privileges Required, Scope, and Security Requirements.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] A new standard method of extending CVSS, called the CVSS Extensions Framework, was also defined, allowing a scoring provider to include additional metrics and metric groups while retaining the official Base, Temporal, and Environmental Metrics.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The additional metrics allow industry sectors such as privacy, safety, automotive, healthcare, etc., to score factors that are outside the core CVSS standard.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Finally, the CVSS Glossary of Terms has been expanded and refined to cover all terms used throughout the CVSSv3.1 documentation.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Version 4.0 was officially released in November 2023, and is available at FIRST.org.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Among several clarifications, the most notable changes are the new base metric *Attack Requirements* which complement the metric *Attack Complexity* with an assessment what conditions at the target side are needed to exploit a vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Further, the *Impact* metrics are split into impact on the vulnerable system itself and impact on subsequent systems (this replaces the *Scope* metric from prior versions).
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Additionally to these base metrics, there are optional metrics regarding public availability of an exploit, environment specific thread modelling, system recovery, and others.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] In January 2026, the standards body released a new Consumer Implementation Guide that details the use of Threat and Environmental metrics to produce scores that more accurately reflect the deployment environment and threat activity.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The guide also introduces a maturity model to explain how these additional metric groups improve scores for improved real-world triage and resource allocation.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] For illustrative purposes, assume there is an SQL injection vulnerability in an online web shop.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] The database user of the online shop software only has read access to the database.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-vulnerability-scoring-system] Further, the injection is in a view of the shop which is only visible to registered customers.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] The **Common Weakness Enumeration** (**CWE**) is a category system for hardware and software weaknesses and vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] It is sustained by a community project with the goals of understanding flaws in software and hardware and creating automated tools that can be used to identify, fix, and prevent those flaws.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] The project is sponsored by the office of the U.S.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), which is operated by The MITRE Corporation, with support from US-CERT and the National Cyber Security Division of the U.S.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] The first release of the list and associated classification taxonomy was in 2006.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] Version 4.15 of the CWE standard was released in July 2024.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] CWE has over 600 categories, including classes for buffer overflows, path/directory tree traversal errors, race conditions, cross-site scripting, hard-coded passwords, and insecure random numbers.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) Compatibility program allows a service or a product to be reviewed and registered as officially "CWE-Compatible" and "CWE-Effective".
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] The program assists organizations in selecting the right software tools and learning about possible weaknesses and their possible impact.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] There are 56 organizations as of September 2019 that develop and maintain products and services that achieved CWE Compatible status.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] Some researchers think that ambiguities in CWE can be avoided or reduced.
[src:cvss-scoring/common-weakness-enumeration] As of 4/16/2024, the CWE Compatibility Program has been discontinued.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] An **exploit** is a method or piece of code that takes advantage of vulnerabilities in software, applications, networks, operating systems, or hardware, typically for malicious purposes.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] The term "exploit" derives from the English verb "to exploit," meaning "to use something to one’s own advantage." Exploits are designed to identify flaws, bypass security measures, gain unauthorized access to systems, take control of systems, install malware, or steal sensitive data.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] While an exploit by itself may not be a malware, it serves as a vehicle for delivering malicious software by breaching security controls.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Estimates of the economic cost of cyberattacks that rely on exploits vary widely depending on methodology and scope; a 2020 McAfee/CSIS report estimated the global cost of cybercrime at more than US$1 trillion annually.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] In response to this threat, organizations are increasingly utilizing cyber threat intelligence to identify vulnerabilities and prevent hacks before they occur.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Exploits target vulnerabilities, which are essentially flaws or weaknesses in a system's defenses.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Common targets for exploits include operating systems, web browsers, and various applications, where hidden vulnerabilities can compromise the integrity and security of computer systems.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Exploits can cause unintended or unanticipated behavior in systems, potentially leading to severe security breaches.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Many exploits are designed to provide superuser-level access to a computer system.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Exploits that remain unknown to everyone except the individuals who discovered and developed them are referred to as zero-day or "0day" exploits.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] After an exploit is disclosed to the authors of the affected software, the associated vulnerability is often fixed through a patch, rendering the exploit unusable.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] This is why some black hat hackers, as well as military or intelligence agency hackers, do not publish their exploits but keep them private.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] One scheme that offers zero-day exploits is known as exploit as a service.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] There are several methods of classifying exploits.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Examples are by the component targeted, or by vulnerability type.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] The most common is by how the exploit communicates to the vulnerable software.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Another classification is by the action against the vulnerable system, such as: unauthorized data access; arbitrary code execution; and denial of service.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] The classification of exploits based on the type of vulnerability they exploit and the result of running the exploit (e.g., elevation of privilege (EoP), denial of service (DoS), spoofing) is a common practice in cybersecurity.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] This approach helps in systematically identifying and addressing security threats.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] For instance, the STRIDE threat model categorizes threats into six types, including Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, and Elevation of Privilege.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Similarly, the National Vulnerability Database (NVD) categorizes vulnerabilities by types such as Authentication Bypass by Spoofing and Authorization Bypass.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Attackers employ various techniques to exploit vulnerabilities and achieve their objectives.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] A zero-click attack is an exploit that requires no user interaction to operate – that is to say, no key-presses or mouse clicks.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] These exploits are commonly the most sought after exploits (specifically on the underground exploit market) because the target typically has no way of knowing they have been compromised at the time of exploitation.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] FORCEDENTRY, discovered in 2021, is an example of a zero-click attack.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] In 2022, NSO Group was reportedly selling zero-click exploits to governments for breaking into individuals' phones.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] For mobile devices, the National Security Agency (NSA) points out that timely updating of software and applications, avoiding public network connections, and turning the device Off and On at least once a week can mitigate the threat of zero-click attacks.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Experts say that protection practices for traditional endpoints are also applicable to mobile devices.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Many exploits exist only in memory, not in files.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Theoretically, restarting the device can wipe malware payloads from memory, forcing attackers back to the beginning of the exploit chain.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Pivoting is a follow-on technique: After an exploit has compromised a system, access to other devices on the network can be gained, so the process repeats; i.e., additional vulnerabilities can be sought and attempts made to exploit those in turn.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Pivoting is employed by both hackers and penetration testers to expand their access within a target network.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] By compromising a system, attackers can leverage it as a platform to target other systems that are typically shielded from direct external access by firewalls.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Internal networks often contain a broader range of accessible machines compared to those exposed to the internet.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] For example, an attacker might compromise a web server on a corporate network and then utilize it to target other systems within the same network.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] This approach is often referred to as a multi-layered attack.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Pivoting is also known as *island hopping*.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Typically, the proxy or VPN applications enabling pivoting are executed on the target computer as the payload of an exploit.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] Pivoting is usually done by infiltrating a part of a network infrastructure (as an example, a vulnerable printer or thermostat) and using a scanner to find other devices connected to attack them.
[src:cvss-scoring/exploit-computer-security] By attacking a vulnerable piece of networking, an attacker could infect most or all of a network and gain complete control.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] In computer security, a **vulnerability** is a flaw or weakness in a system's design, implementation, or management that can be exploited by a malicious actor to compromise its security.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts to achieve complete correctness, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs where the system does not behave as expected.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If the bug could enable an attacker to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of system resources, it can be considered a vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Insecure software development practices as well as design factors such as complexity can increase the burden of vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management includes identifying systems and prioritizing which are most important, scanning for vulnerabilities, and taking action to secure the system.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management typically is a combination of remediation, mitigation, and acceptance.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can be scored for severity according to the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) and added to vulnerability databases such as the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] As of April 2026, more than 327,000 vulnerabilities had been recorded in the CVE database.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] A vulnerability is initiated when it is introduced into hardware or software.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] It becomes active and exploitable when the software or hardware containing the vulnerability is running.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability may be discovered by the administrator, vendor, or a third party.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Publicly disclosing the vulnerability (through a patch or otherwise) is associated with an increased risk of compromise, as attackers can use this knowledge to target existing systems before patches are implemented.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities will eventually end when the system is either patched or removed from use.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Software patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but zero-days are still liable for exploitation.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors, and the actual risk is dependent on the nature of the vulnerability as well as the value of the surrounding system.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Although some vulnerabilities can only be used for denial-of-service attacks, more dangerous ones allow the attacker to perform code injection without the user's awareness.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Only a minority of vulnerabilities allow for privilege escalation, which is typically necessary for more severe attacks.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Without a vulnerability, an exploit typically cannot gain access.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] It is also possible for malware to be installed directly, without an exploit, through social engineering or poor physical security such as an unlocked door or exposed port.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Poor software development practices can affect the likelihood of introducing vulnerabilities to a code base.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Lack of knowledge or training regarding secure software development, excessive pressure to deliver, or an excessively complex code base can all allow vulnerabilities to be introduced and left unnoticed.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] These factors can also be exacerbated if security is not prioritized by the company culture.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Inadequate code reviews can also lead to missed bugs, but there are also static code analysis tools that can be used during the code review process to help find some vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] DevOps, a development workflow that emphasizes automated testing and deployment to speed up the deployment of new features, often requires that many developers be granted access to change configurations, which can lead to deliberate or inadvertent inclusion of vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Compartmentalizing dependencies, which is often part of DevOps workflows, can reduce the attack surface by paring down dependencies to only what is necessary.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If software as a service is used, rather than the organization's own hardware and software, the organization is dependent on the cloud services provider to prevent vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Access control vulnerabilities enable an attacker to access a system that is supposed to be restricted to them, or engage in privilege escalation.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] When the system fails to handle and exceptional or unanticipated condition correctly, an attacker can exploit the situation to gain access.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Configuration vulnerability come into existence when configuration settings cause risks to the system security, leading to such faults as unpatched software or file system permissions that do not sufficiently restrict access.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] A race condition—when timing or other external factors change the outcome and lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results—can cause a vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Deliberate security bugs can be introduced during or after manufacturing and cause the integrated circuit not to behave as expected under certain specific circumstances.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Testing for security bugs in hardware is quite difficult due to limited time and the complexity of twenty-first century chips, while the globalization of design and manufacturing has increased the opportunity for these bugs to be introduced by malicious actors.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Although operating system vulnerabilities vary depending on the operating system in use, a common problem is privilege escalation bugs that enable the attacker to gain more access than they should be allowed.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Open-source operating systems such as Linux and Android have a freely accessible source code and allow anyone to contribute, which could enable the introduction of vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] However, the same vulnerabilities also occur in proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows and Apple operating systems.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] All reputable vendors of operating systems provide patches regularly.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Client–server applications are downloaded onto the end user's computers and are typically updated less frequently than web applications.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Unlike web applications, they interact directly with a user's operating system.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Because they are inherently less secure than other applications, they are a leading source of data breaches and other security incidents.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Although estimating the risk of an attack is not straightforward, the mean time to breach and expected cost can be considered to determine the priority for remediating or mitigating an identified vulnerability and whether it is cost effective to do so.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Successful vulnerability management usually involves a combination of remediation (closing a vulnerability), mitigation (increasing the difficulty, and reducing the consequences, of exploits), and accepting some residual risk.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Often a defense in depth strategy is used for multiple barriers to attack.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Some organizations scan for only the highest-risk vulnerabilities as this enables prioritization in the context of lacking the resources to fix every vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Increasing expenses is likely to have diminishing returns.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Remediation fixes vulnerabilities, for example by downloading a software patch.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability scanners are typically unable to detect zero-day vulnerabilities, but are more effective at finding known vulnerabilities based on a database.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] These systems can find some known vulnerabilities and advise fixes, such as a patch.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] However, they have limitations including false positives.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can only be exploited when they are active-the software in which they are embedded is actively running on the system.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Before the code containing the vulnerability is configured to run on the system, it is considered a carrier.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Dormant vulnerabilities can run, but are not currently running.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Software containing dormant and carrier vulnerabilities can sometimes be uninstalled or disabled, removing the risk.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Active vulnerabilities, if distinguished from the other types, can be prioritized for patching.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability mitigation is measures that do not close the vulnerability, but make it more difficult to exploit or reduce the consequences of an attack.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Reducing the attack surface, particularly for parts of the system with root (administrator) access, and closing off opportunities for exploits to engage in privilege exploitation is a common strategy for reducing the harm that a cyberattack can cause.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If a patch for third-party software is unavailable, it may be possible to temporarily disable the software.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] A penetration test attempts to enter the system via an exploit to see if the system is insecure.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If a penetration test fails, it does not necessarily mean that the system is secure.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Some penetration tests can be conducted with automated software that tests against existing exploits for known vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Other penetration tests are conducted by trained hackers.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Many companies prefer to contract out this work as it simulates an outsider attack.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability lifecycle begins when vulnerabilities are introduced into hardware or software.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Detection of vulnerabilities can be by the software vendor, or by a third party.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] In the latter case, it is considered most ethical to immediately disclose the vulnerability to the vendor so it can be fixed.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Government or intelligence agencies buy vulnerabilities that have not been publicly disclosed and may use them in an attack, stockpile them, or notify the vendor.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] As of 2013, the Five Eyes (United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand) captured the plurality of the market and other significant purchasers included Russia, India, Brazil, Malaysia, Singapore, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Organized criminal groups also buy vulnerabilities, although they typically prefer exploit kits.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Even vulnerabilities that are publicly known or patched are often exploitable for an extended period.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Security patches can take months to develop, or may never be developed.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] A patch can have negative effects on the functionality of software and users may need to test the patch to confirm functionality and compatibility.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Larger organizations may fail to identify and patch all dependencies, while smaller enterprises and personal users may not install patches.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Research suggests that risk of cyberattack increases if the vulnerability is made publicly known or a patch is released.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Cybercriminals can reverse engineer the patch to find the underlying vulnerability and develop exploits, often faster than users install the patch.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities become deprecated when the software or vulnerable versions fall out of use.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] This can take an extended period of time; in particular, industrial software may not be feasible to replace even if the manufacturer stops supporting it.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] A commonly used scale for assessing the severity of vulnerabilities is the open-source specification Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS).
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] CVSS evaluates the possibility to exploit the vulnerability and compromise data confidentiality, availability, and integrity.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] It also considers how the vulnerability could be used and how complex an exploit would need to be.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The amount of access needed for exploitation and whether it could take place without user interaction are also factored in to the overall score.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Someone who discovers a vulnerability may disclose it immediately (full disclosure) or wait until a patch has been developed (responsible disclosure, or coordinated disclosure).
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The former approach is praised for its transparency, but the drawback is that the risk of attack is likely to be increased after disclosure with no patch available.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Some vendors pay bug bounties to those who report vulnerabilities to them.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Not all companies respond positively to disclosures, as they can cause legal liability and operational overhead.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] There is no law requiring disclosure of vulnerabilities.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] If a vulnerability is discovered by a third party that does not disclose to the vendor or the public, it is called a zero-day vulnerability, often considered the most dangerous type because fewer defenses exist.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The most commonly used vulnerability dataset is Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE), maintained by Mitre Corporation.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] This information is shared into other databases, including the United States' National Vulnerability Database, where each vulnerability is given a risk score using Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS), Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) scheme, and Common Weakness Enumeration.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] CVE and other databases typically do not track vulnerabilities in software as a service products.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Submitting a CVE is voluntary for companies that discovered a vulnerability.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] The software vendor is usually not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:cvss-scoring/vulnerability-computing] Some companies are covered by laws, such as PCI, HIPAA, and Sarbanes-Oxley, that place legal requirements on vulnerability management.
